expression.Value: In this tutorial you will learn about expression to create charts.
Category charts are graphics that show numeric information (values) related to strings (the categories). Types of charts used to visualize categorized data are bar charts, line charts and pie charts.

For bar and line charts, usually the categories are displayed in the x-axis, and their values in the y-axis. Because the values is represented as a vertical length, the orientation of the chart is vertical. Charts with the opposite orientations are then called in horizontal orientation.
Creates a bart chart and a line chart, respectively. They use the same syntax and semantics, they only differ in apparience.

For pie charts, categories are represented as slices, where each sector size (its angle) represents its (relative) value. There is no concept of orientation in pie charts.
Width and height of the chart, in pixels
A series is a set of set of attributes (strings) that all (or most of) the categories share, so every value is associated with both a category and a series.
Bar and line chart with categories and series
With bar charts, for every category, several bars are shown (one for each series). Bars representing the same series share the same colors.
For line charts, several lines are shown, one for each series. Each series (line) is represented by a different color.

In XY charts, the values to plot are both numeric. They are like coordinates. The first values (the domain) are drawn horizontally, and the second values are drawn vertically (the range).
Data must be introduced as a list of pairs of numeric values.
